#1 to 120 grazed sites, 121 to 190 ungrazed sites
#to grazed sites eliminate ctenomys fru <- can [1:120, 59:70] fru <- fru[,-10]
#to ungrazed sites do not consider data of Bos taurus and Equus caballus 
#vistis 31:42; fruits consumed 43:54; total effect 59:70

#Grazed sites

#To run CCA only considering visited trees 
#Grazed sites

fruG <- cans [1:108, 31:42]
fruG <- fruG [, -10] #I do not include data of Ctenomys mendocinus in grazed sites, because it did not interact with trees
plantG <- cans [1:108, 4:21]

#Ungrazed sites

fruUG <- cans [109:172, 31:40] #I do not include in analysis data of Bos taurus and Equus caballus for ungrazed land uses
plantUG <- cans [109:172, 4:21]
#well look at the correlations within and between the two sets of variables using the matcor function from the CCA package.
#http://www.statisticssolutions.com/table-of-critical-values-pearson-correlation/

matcor(fruG, plantG)

#Wilks(ccR)

#plot(cc)
#plot(ccR)
#Grazed sites
# tests for canonical variables significancy, the Wilks lambda represents the total variance not explained by the full canonical model. Is  a Test of Significance of the canonical correlation coefficient.
#I adapted the code obtained from https://stats.idre.ucla.edu/r/dae/canonical-correlation-analysis/ (UCLA Statistical Consulting Group, UCLA= University of California in Los ngeles)

ev <- (1 - ccG$cor^2)

n <- dim(fruG)[1]
p <- length(fruG)
q <- length(plantG)
k <- min(p, q)
m <- n - 3/2 - (p + q)/2

w <- rev(cumprod(rev(ev)))

# initialize
d1 <- d2 <- f <- vector("numeric", k)

for (i in 1:k) {
    s <- sqrt((p^2 * q^2 - 4)/(p^2 + q^2 - 5))
    si <- 1/s
    d1[i] <- p * q
    d2[i] <- m * s - p * q/2 + 1
    r <- (1 - w[i]^si)/w[i]^si
    f[i] <- r * d2[i]/d1[i]
    p <- p - 1
    q <- q - 1
}

pv <- pf(f, d1, d2, lower.tail = F, log.p=F)
(dmat <- cbind(WilksL = w, F = f, df1 = d1, df2 = d2, p = pv))
##           WilksL         F df1      df2            p

#Ungrazed sites
# tests for canonical variables significancy, the Wilks lambda represents the total variance not explained by the full canonical model. Is  a Test of Significance of the canonical correlation coefficient.

ev <- (1 - ccUG$cor^2)

n <- dim(fruUG)[1]
p <- length(fruUG)
q <- length(plantUG)
k <- min(p, q)
m <- n - 3/2 - (p + q)/2

w <- rev(cumprod(rev(ev)))

# initialize
d1 <- d2 <- f <- vector("numeric", k)

for (i in 1:k) {
    s <- sqrt((p^2 * q^2 - 4)/(p^2 + q^2 - 5))
    si <- 1/s
    d1[i] <- p * q
    d2[i] <- m * s - p * q/2 + 1
    r <- (1 - w[i]^si)/w[i]^si
    f[i] <- r * d2[i]/d1[i]
    p <- p - 1
    q <- q - 1
}

pv <- pf(f, d1, d2, lower.tail = FALSE)

#Wilks(ccR)

#plot(cc)
#plot(ccR)
#Grazed sites
# tests for canonical variables significancy, the Wilks lambda represents the total variance not explained by the full canonical model. Is  a Test of Significance of the canonical correlation coefficient.
#I adapted the code obtained from https://stats.idre.ucla.edu/r/dae/canonical-correlation-analysis/ (UCLA Statistical Consulting Group, UCLA= University of California in Los ngeles)

ev <- (1 - ccGh$cor^2)

n <- dim(fruG)[1]
p <- length(fruG)
q <- length(plantGh)
k <- min(p, q)
m <- n - 3/2 - (p + q)/2

w <- rev(cumprod(rev(ev)))

# initialize
d1 <- d2 <- f <- vector("numeric", k)

for (i in 1:k) {
    s <- sqrt((p^2 * q^2 - 4)/(p^2 + q^2 - 5))
    si <- 1/s
    d1[i] <- p * q
    d2[i] <- m * s - p * q/2 + 1
    r <- (1 - w[i]^si)/w[i]^si
    f[i] <- r * d2[i]/d1[i]
    p <- p - 1
    q <- q - 1
}

pv <- pf(f, d1, d2, lower.tail = F, log.p=F)
(dmat <- cbind(WilksL = w, F = f, df1 = d1, df2 = d2, p = pv))
##         WilksL          F df1      df2            p
## [1,] 0.2582644 2.14772232  66 492.3831 2.354336e-06
## [2,] 0.5518131 1.17784169  50 422.9488 1.990562e-01
## [3,] 0.7428786 0.80307906  36 350.2514 7.854861e-01
## [4,] 0.9076474 0.38678463  24 273.2298 9.963425e-01
## [5,] 0.9640036 0.25106009  14 190.0000 9.974624e-01
## [6,] 0.9976296 0.03801684   6  96.0000 9.997598e-01
#Grazed sites
# tests for canonical variables significancy, the Wilks lambda represents the total variance not explained by the full canonical model. Is  a Test of Significance of the canonical correlation coefficient.
#I adapted the code obtained from https://stats.idre.ucla.edu/r/dae/canonical-correlation-analysis/ (UCLA Statistical Consulting Group, UCLA= University of California in Los ngeles)

ev <- (1 - ccUGh$cor^2)

n <- dim(fruUG)[1]
p <- length(fruUG)
q <- length(plantUGh)
k <- min(p, q)
m <- n - 3/2 - (p + q)/2

w <- rev(cumprod(rev(ev)))

# initialize
d1 <- d2 <- f <- vector("numeric", k)

for (i in 1:k) {
    s <- sqrt((p^2 * q^2 - 4)/(p^2 + q^2 - 5))
    si <- 1/s
    d1[i] <- p * q
    d2[i] <- m * s - p * q/2 + 1
    r <- (1 - w[i]^si)/w[i]^si
    f[i] <- r * d2[i]/d1[i]
    p <- p - 1
    q <- q - 1
}

pv <- pf(f, d1, d2, lower.tail = F, log.p=F)
(dmat <- cbind(WilksL = w, F = f, df1 = d1, df2 = d2, p = pv))
